WEBVTT

00:05.839 --> 00:08.742
<i>[upbeat music]</i>

00:08.842 --> 00:15.915
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:32.499 --> 00:34.267
- Excuse me.

00:34.367 --> 00:35.935
- Hi, yeah.

00:36.036 --> 00:39.105
- Uh, do you have any copies
of a book called "Exit West"?

00:39.205 --> 00:40.407
- [laughs]

00:40.507 --> 00:43.777
I'm sorry.
I don't work here, actually.

00:43.877 --> 00:47.447
- Oh. Wow, um, I'm sorry.

00:47.547 --> 00:50.116
It's just, I saw you
putting books on the table,

00:50.216 --> 00:51.418
so I assumed...

00:51.518 --> 00:53.119
- Yeah--no,
that's a fair assumption.

00:53.219 --> 00:56.723
Um, actually, I have a special
investment in this book

00:56.790 --> 00:59.092
because I edited it.

00:59.192 --> 01:01.761
It got an unfair review
from "New York Times."

01:01.861 --> 01:03.563
I'm just trying to make sure
it gets some love.

01:03.630 --> 01:05.465
But it's a great book.
I guarantee it.

01:05.565 --> 01:06.866
- Okay.

01:06.933 --> 01:08.635
- You'll like it,
or your money back,

01:08.735 --> 01:09.969
no questions asked.

01:10.070 --> 01:11.805
- [laughs]

01:11.905 --> 01:14.207
- As a writer myself, I'm sure
they appreciate your advocacy.

01:14.274 --> 01:17.710
- Oh, really?
Anything I might have read?

01:17.777 --> 01:19.712
- I'm a playwright.

01:19.779 --> 01:22.148
- Okay.
Anything I might have seen?

01:22.248 --> 01:23.616
- I don't know.

01:23.716 --> 01:26.152
Are you into the Houston
independent theater scene?

01:26.252 --> 01:28.822
- [laughs] Uh...
- Yeah. [laughs]

01:28.922 --> 01:31.558
- Well, I'm sure
it's only a matter of time.

01:31.624 --> 01:35.128
- It's Ola, by the way.

01:35.228 --> 01:37.464
- Marcus.
Nice to meet you.

01:37.564 --> 01:38.731
- Nice to meet you.

01:40.233 --> 01:43.503
- So I should probably get
out of here before they see me

01:43.603 --> 01:47.307
moving their books around,
but...I don't know.

01:47.407 --> 01:50.310
Maybe we could grab
a drink sometime?

01:51.945 --> 01:53.746
- Uh, you know, to be honest,

01:53.813 --> 01:55.849
you're kind of catching me
at a bad time.

01:55.949 --> 01:57.417
I leave town on Sunday

01:57.484 --> 01:59.152
to go to an artist residency
in Vermont.

01:59.252 --> 02:00.420
- Uh-huh.
- Yeah.

02:00.487 --> 02:02.489
Got six weeks
to workshop a play

02:02.589 --> 02:04.090
I've been writing
for three years.

02:04.157 --> 02:05.258
- Oh.
- Yeah.

02:05.325 --> 02:06.826
I should really focus on that.

02:06.926 --> 02:07.994
- Okay.
- Yeah.

02:08.094 --> 02:09.496
- Yeah.

02:09.596 --> 02:15.201
But are you sure you can't
focus and have a drink?

02:15.301 --> 02:22.008
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:29.983 --> 02:31.050
- Pshh.

02:34.654 --> 02:36.990
- Oh, hey, man.

02:37.056 --> 02:38.725
What's going on?

02:38.825 --> 02:41.294
- Well, you clearly see
what is going on.

02:42.228 --> 02:43.396
So what are you doing?

02:43.496 --> 02:44.564
Picking up chicks
in a bookstore

02:44.664 --> 02:46.699
like an off-brand Hugh Grant?

02:46.799 --> 02:49.736
- You know, actually,
it was--it was Hugh Grant

02:49.836 --> 02:51.838
that got picked up
by Julia Roberts

02:51.905 --> 02:54.240
in "Notting Hill,"
so joke's on you.

02:54.340 --> 02:55.842
- No, I think the joke's
still on you

02:55.909 --> 02:57.577
for remembering the plot
to fucking "Notting Hill."

02:57.677 --> 03:00.146
- Well, I saw
that Claudette Jeffries

03:00.213 --> 03:01.915
got published.

03:02.015 --> 03:04.050
She was in your
MFA program, right?

03:04.150 --> 03:06.753
- Yeah, she wrote about
a rich lady in domestic peril.

03:06.853 --> 03:08.555
You write about a rich woman
in domestic peril,

03:08.655 --> 03:10.023
the book's gonna sell.

03:10.089 --> 03:11.891
- It's still 150K advance.
That must be nice.

03:11.991 --> 03:13.760
I mean, maybe you like
working here.

03:13.860 --> 03:15.094
- Dude, relax, Marcus Watkins.

03:15.195 --> 03:16.663
Don't come here
and fucking gloat

03:16.729 --> 03:18.164
like I would've been
the next Octavia Butler

03:18.231 --> 03:19.666
if I fucked with you.

03:19.732 --> 03:21.267
I saw you moving the books
around on the shelf

03:21.367 --> 03:22.902
like that was gonna help it
fly out of here.

03:23.002 --> 03:24.437
- Well, at least
it's published.

03:24.537 --> 03:26.105
- Yeah, it's a lot of things
in here published.

03:26.206 --> 03:30.376
- All right, listen,
in spite of all this attitude

03:30.443 --> 03:34.280
you're giving me right now,
I actually like your writing.

03:34.948 --> 03:37.283
Like, I really like it,

03:37.383 --> 03:39.552
and the offer still stands.

03:39.619 --> 03:41.854
You take care of yourself.

03:41.921 --> 03:45.358
You have my number
when you're ready to act right.

03:46.426 --> 03:47.894
- Damn!

03:49.229 --> 03:52.198
<i>[upbeat music playing]</i>

03:52.265 --> 03:56.903
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:56.970 --> 03:57.937
- Hi.

03:58.037 --> 04:01.641
- Hi.
- Oh, well, hello.

04:01.741 --> 04:03.042
- You look beautiful.

04:03.109 --> 04:04.377
- Thank you.
- Yeah.

04:04.444 --> 04:06.879
So first date--
let's get into it.

04:06.946 --> 04:09.048
- Is that what this is?
I thought this was drinks.

04:09.115 --> 04:11.251
- Oh, yeah, well, drinking
is a very important part

04:11.317 --> 04:12.652
of first dates.

04:12.752 --> 04:15.421
- Oh, okay.
You know, your enthusiasm

04:15.488 --> 04:18.825
means you either date
constantly or hardly ever.

04:18.925 --> 04:20.159
- Ah, man.

04:20.260 --> 04:22.095
Wow, you are definitely
a playwright.

04:22.161 --> 04:23.496
You're already trying
to figure me out.

04:23.596 --> 04:25.164
- So which one is it?
- Damn.

04:25.265 --> 04:27.300
Um, you know, actually,
it's kind of both.

04:27.400 --> 04:31.170
- Okay. All right.
Let's get into it.

04:31.271 --> 04:33.439
My story. Okay, let's see.

04:33.506 --> 04:34.907
I was born in Lagos.
- Mm-hmm.

04:34.974 --> 04:36.576
- Moved to Houston
when I was six.

04:36.643 --> 04:38.177
Dad was a civil engineer.

04:38.278 --> 04:39.679
Mom is a superintendent.

04:39.779 --> 04:41.147
- Classic
high-achieving Nigerians.

04:41.247 --> 04:42.515
- So you know?
- Oh, yeah.

04:42.615 --> 04:44.817
- Okay.
A lot of people don't know.

04:44.917 --> 04:47.920
- So how do your parents feel
about you being a playwright?

04:47.987 --> 04:49.589
- They don't love it, no.

04:49.656 --> 04:52.458
But I didn't love biotech,
so now we can all be unhappy.

04:52.525 --> 04:54.861
- Wait, hang on.
Wait, I'm sorry, biotech?

04:54.961 --> 04:56.029
- Mm-hmm.

04:56.129 --> 04:57.664
- Oh, man,
so you're like a genius.

04:57.764 --> 04:59.365
- You know, I had the idea
for Theranos

04:59.465 --> 05:01.467
before that white girl ran off
with everybody's money,

05:01.534 --> 05:03.703
except mine
would've worked out.

05:03.803 --> 05:05.438
- All right.
- I would've followed through.

05:05.505 --> 05:07.974
- I don't know, it sounds like
a whole scam to me, so...

05:08.041 --> 05:10.443
- Oh, wow, you're gonna do
the Nigerian scam thing.

05:10.510 --> 05:11.878
- [laughs] Okay, you're right.
You're right.

05:11.978 --> 05:13.212
You're right.
I'm sorry, I'm sorry.

05:13.313 --> 05:14.714
- So what,
'cause I'm an immigrant,

05:14.814 --> 05:16.049
my work has to grapple

05:16.149 --> 05:17.850
with being caught
between two worlds?

05:17.950 --> 05:19.352
[both laugh]

05:19.452 --> 05:22.221
Or, like, function
as some postcolonial critique

05:22.322 --> 05:23.723
of the diaspora?

05:23.823 --> 05:27.160
No, no, no, real progress
is getting to tell a story

05:27.226 --> 05:28.861
about my alcoholic aunt
and her daughter

05:28.961 --> 05:30.396
who live on Long Island,
like white writers.

05:30.496 --> 05:32.398
- Yes, yes, I want you
to tell that story.

05:32.498 --> 05:34.467
- I'm really--that's why--
that's why my play

05:34.534 --> 05:36.569
is about a girl and her dad,
you know,

05:36.669 --> 05:37.870
and I felt like that was

05:37.970 --> 05:39.472
the most radical thing
I could write.

05:39.539 --> 05:41.007
- That sounds amazing.

05:41.074 --> 05:42.375
You know, if--

05:43.843 --> 05:47.580
If you want another set
of eyes on it...

05:50.016 --> 05:52.418
- Mm, I don't know.
I don't know.

05:52.518 --> 05:54.253
- Why?

05:54.354 --> 05:56.989
- Well, I don't usually let

05:57.056 --> 06:00.093
the men I get involved with
read my work.

06:00.193 --> 06:01.928
- Oh.
- Mm-hmm.

06:02.028 --> 06:06.599
- Oh, so you think
we're gonna get involved?

06:06.699 --> 06:08.167
- Maybe.
- Maybe?

06:08.234 --> 06:09.602
- Mm.
- Yeah?

06:09.702 --> 06:12.839
[siren wailing in distance]

06:17.043 --> 06:19.112
- Okay, fine, you can read it.

06:19.212 --> 06:21.347
- Oh, snap.

06:21.414 --> 06:23.616
Savage.
- [chuckles]

06:23.716 --> 06:25.752
- You hurt my heart.
- [laughs]

06:25.852 --> 06:29.222
<i>narrator: Although Marcus</i>
<i>didn't exactly feel fireworks,</i>

06:29.288 --> 06:31.958
<i>he told himself</i>
<i>that a spark was enough,</i>

06:32.058 --> 06:34.460
<i>for a spark might eventually</i>
<i>lead to a fire,</i>

06:34.560 --> 06:36.295
<i>whereas in his experience,</i>

06:36.396 --> 06:41.033
<i>fireworks had only ever led</i>
<i>to an explosion.</i>

06:41.100 --> 06:42.635
- What's up
with the empty fridge?

06:42.735 --> 06:46.139
- Oh, yeah, I'm sorry.
It's slim pickings, I know.

06:46.239 --> 06:47.373
- It's okay.

06:47.440 --> 06:48.808
You know,
I'll just have some water.

06:48.908 --> 06:50.977
- Okay, that I can do.

06:52.645 --> 06:55.214
- Thank you.
- Mm-hmm.

07:01.888 --> 07:03.156
Hmm.
- Wow.

07:03.256 --> 07:05.158
Busting out
the fine China for me, huh?

07:05.258 --> 07:06.659
- Yeah.
- [laughs]

07:06.759 --> 07:08.561
I should probably get going.

07:08.628 --> 07:10.897
I have a bunch of errands
to run before I leave town.

07:10.963 --> 07:14.567
- Oh, right, right.
Well, damn.

07:14.634 --> 07:16.335
That's a bummer.
You're leaving town tomorrow.

07:16.436 --> 07:17.670
- Yeah.

07:18.671 --> 07:20.440
- You know,
if you gotta run errands,

07:20.506 --> 07:23.309
I mean, would you--
would you want some company?

07:23.409 --> 07:24.677
- I'd love some company.
- Yeah?

07:24.777 --> 07:25.845
- Yeah,
and while we're out there,

07:25.945 --> 07:27.513
let's get you some new cups.

07:27.613 --> 07:29.515
- Okay, dope.
- Yeah.

07:29.615 --> 07:32.585
<i>[soft piano music]</i>

07:32.652 --> 07:36.923
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:36.989 --> 07:38.858
- You know, they got an IKEA
in Red Hook.

07:38.958 --> 07:41.027
- Mm-mm, be better than IKEA.

07:41.127 --> 07:42.261
- [sighs]

07:42.328 --> 07:44.530
I needed that little jolt.
- Yeah.

07:44.630 --> 07:46.299
- I was kind of fading there
for a second.

07:46.365 --> 07:48.935
- Right, I felt it.
- Yeah?

07:49.001 --> 07:52.672
- Yeah, I was like,
"He's not doing too well."

07:53.840 --> 07:57.710
Can I--can I ask you something?

07:58.811 --> 07:59.879
- Yeah, sure.

08:01.147 --> 08:03.182
- What are you looking for?

08:03.282 --> 08:04.717
- Wait a minute.

08:04.817 --> 08:06.552
I thought you were focused
on your work right now.

08:06.652 --> 08:07.987
- Okay.

08:08.054 --> 08:10.456
Yeah, I mean, I was,

08:10.523 --> 08:13.025
but that was before
I kind of liked you.

08:13.125 --> 08:15.328
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:15.394 --> 08:18.865
Look, I've had my fill
of fuck boys,

08:18.965 --> 08:23.736
and I just really wanna make
sure we're on the same page.

08:23.836 --> 08:26.172
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:26.239 --> 08:29.075
- After my divorce,
I dated a lot,

08:29.175 --> 08:31.310
and I gotta be honest.

08:31.377 --> 08:33.479
I'm tired.

08:33.546 --> 08:35.381
- Oh, you're so tired?
- Yeah.

08:35.481 --> 08:38.084
- You're so tired of being
a single, employed,

08:38.184 --> 08:39.752
attractive man
in New York City.

08:39.852 --> 08:41.654
- Oh...
- It's exhausting.

08:41.721 --> 08:44.924
- Hush. I need--
- Stop, stop, stop, stop!

08:45.024 --> 08:46.592
[both laughing]

08:46.692 --> 08:50.696
- No, but for real, like,
the small talk, the banter,

08:50.763 --> 08:57.603
the pretending to be someone
that you're not is just...

08:57.703 --> 08:59.238
I don't know, I...

08:59.338 --> 09:05.611
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:05.711 --> 09:08.180
I'm just looking
for something real.

09:08.247 --> 09:15.354
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:20.726 --> 09:22.628
All right.
- All right.

09:22.728 --> 09:24.697
- Have fun, I guess.
- Thank you.

09:24.764 --> 09:25.965
- All right?
- Yeah.

09:26.065 --> 09:27.400
- All right.
- Okay.

09:33.406 --> 09:37.476
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:37.577 --> 09:40.580
- And we're hoping
to squeeze in a 20-city tour.

09:40.646 --> 09:43.583
Oh, that is marketing
right now.

09:43.649 --> 09:46.886
[phone buzzing]
Let me call you back.

09:46.953 --> 09:48.654
Hi. How are you?

09:48.754 --> 09:50.990
- Hi. I'm good.
I'm so good.

09:51.090 --> 09:53.726
It's really fun, but New
England is fucking freezing.

09:53.793 --> 09:55.494
- Where'd you think you
were headed, Miami beach?

09:55.595 --> 09:57.330
- Okay, smart ass.

09:57.430 --> 09:59.799
<i>- All right,</i>
<i>I'm sending you a sweater.</i>

10:01.601 --> 10:02.935
- The name's Ola Adebayo.

10:03.002 --> 10:04.437
I just texted you the address.

10:04.503 --> 10:07.340
- Oh, someone's sprung.
- Yeah.

10:08.608 --> 10:09.842
Okay, look, I know
what you're going for here,

10:09.942 --> 10:11.110
but this is way too wordy,

10:11.177 --> 10:12.578
so I say we cut it.

10:12.645 --> 10:16.649
- The whole thing?
- Yeah, the whole...thing.

10:16.749 --> 10:18.317
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:18.417 --> 10:19.819
- Yo, what's good?

10:19.919 --> 10:23.022
- So, uh, we cutting
this 'graph, or what?

10:23.122 --> 10:24.457
- Dude, I really think
this last sentence is--

10:24.523 --> 10:26.325
- Look, I know
it's uncomfortable,

10:26.425 --> 10:28.761
but you have to be willing
to kill your darlings.

10:28.828 --> 10:30.529
- Fuck it, bro,
I'll cut it as long as

10:30.630 --> 10:32.798
you don't say another corny-ass
phrase like that ever.

10:32.865 --> 10:35.434
- [laughs]
She's so stupid.

10:35.501 --> 10:36.769
- Dude!

10:36.836 --> 10:38.638
- I loved it.

10:38.704 --> 10:40.873
- You don't have to say that
just because you feel like--

10:40.973 --> 10:44.543
- Ola, I never lie to writers.

10:44.644 --> 10:45.878
<i>- [laughs] Okay.</i>

10:45.978 --> 10:47.213
- Okay. All right.

10:47.313 --> 10:50.116
I rarely lie to writers,
but no, seriously,

10:50.182 --> 10:52.551
this, it's really, really good.

10:52.652 --> 10:55.388
<i>And the world just felt</i>
<i>so lived in.</i>

10:55.488 --> 10:57.056
<i>I mean, I have</i>
<i>a few small thoughts</i>

10:57.156 --> 10:58.691
<i>I could send you</i>
<i>if that's helpful?</i>

10:58.791 --> 10:59.892
- Okay, well, no,
a few small thoughts?

10:59.992 --> 11:01.193
I thought it was perfect.

11:01.293 --> 11:04.530
- Oh, Jesus Christ,
I hate writers.

11:05.297 --> 11:08.501
[phone buzzing]

11:08.567 --> 11:09.502
- Hey, babe.

11:09.568 --> 11:10.970
<i>- Oh, my God, Marcus.</i>

11:11.037 --> 11:12.905
<i>Um, something happened</i>
<i>to my apartment.</i>

11:13.005 --> 11:14.407
- What are you talking about?

11:14.507 --> 11:16.242
<i>- I got this text</i>
<i>from my super</i>

11:16.342 --> 11:18.044
<i>that a pipe burst and a bunch</i>
<i>of apartments flooded.</i>

11:18.144 --> 11:20.012
<i>I'm just still</i>
<i>five hours away,</i>

11:20.079 --> 11:22.248
<i>and I'm so worried</i>
<i>about my fucking cat,</i>

11:22.348 --> 11:23.883
<i>and my cat sitter's MIA.</i>

11:23.983 --> 11:25.384
- It's gonna be all right.

11:25.484 --> 11:27.019
I'm gonna go over there
and get him right now.

11:27.086 --> 11:28.654
Okay?
<i>- Okay.</i>

11:28.721 --> 11:30.556
- All right.

11:32.024 --> 11:36.929
- Oh. Oh, sweet Hansberry.
Oh, sweetie.

11:37.029 --> 11:39.598
I have something for you.
- What?

11:41.200 --> 11:44.537
- Courtesy of Brattleboro's
finest local craftsmen.

11:44.603 --> 11:48.074
- Yo, thank you!
- Of course. You like it?

11:48.174 --> 11:49.575
- Yeah, I love it.

11:51.077 --> 11:52.578
- I have a confession.

11:52.678 --> 11:54.013
[cat meows]

11:54.080 --> 11:58.117
- Hansberry ain't your cat.
- No, no, gosh.

11:58.217 --> 12:00.953
The day before I met you,
my psychic told me

12:01.053 --> 12:04.457
I would be swept off my feet
by a handsome Libra.

12:06.058 --> 12:08.627
- You--you have a psychic?
- Okay, see, do not do that.

12:08.728 --> 12:09.795
That's why
I waited to tell you.

12:09.895 --> 12:11.430
I didn't wanna tell you.

12:11.530 --> 12:13.099
- Not even that you saw
a psychic, you have a psychic.

12:13.199 --> 12:15.301
- Okay, when is your birthday?
- October 13th.

12:15.401 --> 12:16.702
- So you're a fucking Libra,

12:16.769 --> 12:18.738
and a little handsome.
- [laughs]

12:18.804 --> 12:20.306
- Decent.
[phone buzzing]

12:20.406 --> 12:21.974
- All right.
- Hold on.

12:22.074 --> 12:24.643
I gotta take this.
It's my super.

12:24.744 --> 12:27.146
Hey, Victor.

12:27.246 --> 12:28.581
Uh-huh.

12:30.583 --> 12:31.884
For real?

12:33.753 --> 12:36.989
Okay, yeah, um, could you
just keep me posted, please?

12:37.089 --> 12:39.992
Yeah, thank you.

12:40.092 --> 12:42.128
Fuck.

12:43.295 --> 12:44.396
- What's up?

12:44.463 --> 12:46.499
- They found mold in the walls.

12:46.599 --> 12:48.901
Mm-hmm.
- No. Shit.

12:48.968 --> 12:51.637
- Yeah, shit is right.

12:51.737 --> 12:53.439
Ugh, it's such bad timing.

12:56.776 --> 12:59.245
- Why don't you
just stay here

12:59.311 --> 13:01.013
until it all gets sorted out?

13:01.113 --> 13:03.115
- Really?
- Yeah.

13:03.182 --> 13:05.451
I mean, I wouldn't offer it
if I didn't mean it.

13:07.586 --> 13:08.788
- Okay.
- Okay.

13:08.854 --> 13:10.790
- Okay, um...

13:10.856 --> 13:12.191
I just need to grab
a few things

13:12.291 --> 13:13.492
from my place, if that's cool.

13:13.592 --> 13:14.994
- Sure.

13:15.094 --> 13:16.695
- Cool.

